				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Don't be too hard on yourself<a name="41651"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 24 04 3:59 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>yes very well said. Perhaps your path isn't that of a soloist bard there are many many forms of a bard. There is the battle bard  more likely to stand toe to toe and doing battle song and swinging weapons. The charmer an expert on timing mezes and charms  and keeping situations undercontrol that would make a enchanter's jaw drop. The instrumentist that uses songs to their full potential with magical instruments to fortify their group with power they may not even realize they had untill you are gone . The soloist the one that is able to kill mobs that groups would fear touching with little to no harm to themself. I am sure there can be others  if you thout long enough.
<br />

<br />
A bard is the true jack of all trades but the person behind the bard can help them specilize in something I have a guildie that his play style he is more of a battle bard and can handle mobs upclose better then I can. Myself I choose to take the path of the song/charmer and worked on my timing for my mezes ,it is often that I mezzed stuff just when they have goten in their melle range since I knew when it was going to hit,and using instruments when possible to enhance my songs the best I can.
<br />

<br />
I perfer the cha dex route for arsenal while my guidle did the str sta route with some in cha due to the function of bard needing it and the stats on bardic armor.
<br />

<br />
In short a bard can be many things it is just how you wish to use your bard that defines it. You said you was a beastlord  maybe you should look into more of a battle bard and become a singer of songs for haste and strengthing.
<br />

<br />
ok its late enough forsome reason I keep typing even though I should go to sleep and stop trying to edit this to make it look better and more readable due to my horrible typos.</span></td>
