				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Don't be too hard on yourself<a name="41740"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 24 04 11:28 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I agree with the notion both the notion of &quot;not being too hard on yourself&quot; and of &quot;grouping the bard.&quot; I don't care for soloing, but like many bards before LDoN, I sure did a lot of it. I would only add the following to the conversation:
<br />

<br />
Getting good at soloing, as much as I don't care for it, has had a number of benefits. Many of the techniques I practiced over and over and over again when soloing are beneficial to pulling. These techniques were repeated so often, they are now committed to muscle memory. Soloing also demands the bard learn to use macros and UI constructions innovatively and efficiently (many have generously contributed guides). Soloing teaches confidence, even if the confidence is only to know that dying from time to time is part of the game. Soloing teaches methods of no-tank grouping (e.g. the caster circle, where the bard chants the mob in a loop around a camp of casters). And so on.
<br />

<br />
I personally think that we bards learn to master our class in a group and indoors. However, the methods and techniques practiced soloing outdoors helps shape and improve our capability in groups. 
<br />

<br />
I encourage you not to give up on playing the bard, in any event, as I think we all went through similar periods of frustration.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
