				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Don't be too hard on yourself<a name="41752"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 24 04 11:58 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Depending on which soloing technique you use, it might be easier or harder....
<br />

<br />
I'd say chant kiting is easiest of all, pull one mob, chant it down, only thing to that is twisting your dots...
<br />

<br />
Fear kiting isn't too bad either, but I never did it in my 20's and now there's much better methods to get exp (not to mention most mobs are immune to fear now).
<br />

<br />
Swarming is great fun, nowhere near as risky as AoE kiting, the trickiest part about swarming is timing invis right, nothing sucks more than losing 3 mobs to slow invis on a 10 mob kite (when I started swarming I either lost my mob or I'd end up breaking charm way too soon).  Now I'm loving swarming as a way to solo exp when I don't have time to group.  Other than freak occurences, swarming isn't too risky (tho I've had times when my mind like shut off and I turned into my swarm without even thinking about it :p).
<br />

<br />
AoE kiting is the hardest I'd say, if you get hit and stunned, you're prolly dead.  When swarming you can keep your distance, and you're usually not kiting as many mobs.  AoE kiting can be very cool to do, nothing like agro'ing half dulak and killing it all (I've seen a bard who literally pulled half dulak and killed everything, he got almost a full AA for it, I never cared for AoE kiting so I generally don't do it, much prefer swarming). :p
<br />

<br />
There's plenty of methods to solo exp as bard, just pick whichever you like. <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" /> Chant or fear kiting are kinda slow, especially compared to swarm or aoe kiting, but in the case of chant kiting, it's much much safer (and with a tdok you can put out so very respectable damage chant kiting).</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
